# Crawl–Walk–Run: Quote‑to‑Cash Maturity

Someone asked me to name a process I created from scratch.
My honest answer: I’ve never created anything from scratch — and neither has anyone else.

Every process has a seed.
In early SaaS, that seed is a simple contract and invoice.
Even if the company is running on QuickBooks, modified cash, and ignoring standards like ASC 340, ASC 350, or ASC 606, the contracting step exists.
It drives everything downstream.

That’s the beginning of quote‑to‑cash.
Not a blank page — a starting point.

Here’s how that starting point matures:

𝗖𝗥𝗔𝗪𝗟  
• Stage: young, scrappy, founder‑driven
• Pain: inconsistent contracts, cash‑basis revenue, no ASC compliance, billing errors, no customer metrics
• Goal: stabilize contracting and invoicing so cash collection becomes predictable

𝗪𝗔𝗟𝗞  
• Stage: growing, feeling scale pressure, introducing structure
• Pain: unclear billing triggers, inconsistent renewals, partial capitalization, early audit friction, reporting gaps
• Goal: standardize quote‑to‑cash with templates, controls, capitalization, and early ASC 606 alignment

𝗥𝗨𝗡  
• Stage: mature, integrated, insight‑driven
• Pain: strategic only — pricing, churn, expansion, forecasting accuracy
• Goal: fully automate and integrate quote‑to‑cash so revenue, billing, and customer metrics flow cleanly into forecasting and decision‑making
